{"title_page": "Robin Vos", "text_new": "Robbie vos is an ignorant republican't politician who will be charged with attempted murder for risking the lives of voters playing political games and showing no care for human life.  See dirt bag loser in the dictionary. {{short description|American politician and businessman}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name            = Robin Vos\n|image           = Robin Vos speaks at Racine Tea Party event (8378614585).jpg\n|office          = 75th Speaker of the [[Wisconsin State Assembly|Wisconsin Assembly]]\n|term_start      = January 7, 2013\n|term_end        = \n|predecessor     = [[Jeff Fitzgerald]]\n|successor       = \n|state_assembly1 = Wisconsin\n|district1       = 63rd\n|term_start1     = January 3, 2005\n|term_end1       = \n|predecessor1    = [[Bonnie Ladwig]]\n|successor1      = \n|birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1968|7|5}}\n|birth_place     = [[Burlington, Wisconsin|Burlington]], [[Wisconsin]], U.S.\n|death_date      = \n|death_place     = \n|spouse          = Amy Kuemmel {{sup|(2000\u20132003)}}<br>Samantha Schmitt {{sup|(2008\u20132017)}}<br>[[Michelle Litjens]] {{sup|(2017\u2013present)}}\n|party           = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|education       = [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Whitewater]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}\n}}\n'''Robin J. Vos''' (born July 5, 1968) is an American [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[politician]] and the 75th [[Speaker (politics)|Speaker]] of the [[Wisconsin State Assembly]]. He has been a member of the Assembly since 2005,<ref>[http://legis.wisconsin.gov/Pages/leg-info-bio.aspx?h=A&d=63 Profile], legis.wisconsin.gov; accessed November 15, 2014.</ref> representing [[Racine County, Wisconsin|Racine County]], and has been Speaker since 2013.<ref>''Wisconsin Blue Book 2011-2012'', Biographical sketch of Robin Vos, p. 61.</ref> Vos is the President of [[National Conference of State Legislatures]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ncsl.org/press-room/wisconsin-speaker-robin-vos-to-head-ncsl.aspx|title=Wisconsin Speaker Robin Vos to Head NCSL|last=|first=|date=19 August 2019|website=National Conference of State Legislatures|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAfter Democratic nominee [[Tony Evers]] won the [[2018 Wisconsin gubernatorial election]], defeating incumbent Republican governor [[Scott Walker (politician)|Scott Walker]], Vos sought to curb the incoming governor's powers.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Early life and education ==\nVos was born on July 5, 1968, in [[Burlington, Wisconsin]], in the southwest corner of [[Racine County, Wisconsin|Racine County]]. He graduated from [[Burlington High School (Wisconsin)|Burlington High School]] in 1986.\n\nVos attended the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Whitewater]], where he studied political science and public relations. While at Whitewater, he roomed with [[Reince Priebus]], who later became Chairman of the [[Republican Party of Wisconsin]], Chairman of the [[Republican National Committee]], and the 27th [[White House Chief of Staff]]. In 1989, [[Governor of Wisconsin|Wisconsin Governor]] [[Tommy Thompson]] appointed Vos as a student representative on the [[University of Wisconsin System|University of Wisconsin]] Board of Regents. Vos graduated in 1991.<ref name=\"madVos\">{{cite web|url=https://madison.com/robin-vos-timeline/article_ce58f640-24d2-5fdb-9c8f-ce3a3930ba88.html |title= Robin Vos Timeline |publisher= [[Wisconsin State Journal]]|date=2018-12-22|accessdate=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter graduation, Vos worked as a [[legislative assistant]] to State Representatives [[E. James Ladwig|Jim Ladwig]] and [[Bonnie Ladwig]].<ref name=\"madVos\"/> 1994 Vos was elected to the Racine County Board of Supervisors. He remained on the board for the next 10 years.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Robin_Vos|title=Robin Vos - Ballotpedia|access-date=2017-10-26|language=en-US}}</ref> After the election Vos worked as district director for State Representative [[Mark Neumann]].<ref name=\"madVos\" />\n\nIn 1996 Vos purchased the RoJos Popcorn Company in Burlington.<ref name=\"madVos\" /><ref>[http://journaltimes.com/news/local/robin-vos-the-man-amidst-the-controversy/article_49a6cbd0-b5ae-11e0-af68-001cc4c03286.html \"Robin Vos, the man amidst the controversy\"], journaltimes.com; accessed November 15, 2014.</ref>\n\nIn 2004 Vos ran for the Wisconsin State Assembly to succeed Ladwig in the 63rd district. He was unopposed in the 2004 primary and general elections.\n\nAfter Republicans won full control of government in Wisconsin in 2010, Vos rose to prominence pushing the controversial [[2011 Wisconsin Act 10|budget restructuring]] act alongside Governor [[Scott Walker (politician)|Scott Walker]]. The law curtailed collective bargaining rights and public education funding in Wisconsin, and led to massive protests around the state, culminating in the 2012 [[Wisconsin gubernatorial recall election]].<ref name=\"madVos\"/>\n\nIn 2013, Vos was elected Speaker of the Wisconsin Assembly.<ref name=\"madVos\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://legis.wisconsin.gov/assembly/63/vos/about-robin/biography/|title=Robin J. Vos}}</ref> Between 2014 and 2018 he received about $57,000 in travel and perks from lobbyists and organizations. He said he was certain he had followed ethics rules with his travel.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">Patrick Marley. \"[https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/politics/2018/05/03/robin-vos-last-year-received-13-000-travel-and-other-perks/577176002/ Assembly Speaker Robin Vos received $57,000 in travel and other perks since 2014]\". ''Milwaukee Journal Sentinel'', May 3, 2018.</ref><ref>Julie Carr Smyth. [http://host.madison.com/wsj/news/local/govt-and-politics/robin-vos-among-gop-leaders-who-made-trip-with-lobbyists/article_960e561d-94f5-51ce-8c06-3e735dd2cd94.html Robin Vos among GOP leaders who made trip with lobbyists and controversial lawmaker]\". ''Wisconsin State Journal'', April 18, 2018.</ref><ref>Jason Stein and Patrick Marley. \"[https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/politics/2018/04/12/wisconsin-speaker-robin-vos-took-free-trip-london-lobbyists-and-leaders-other-states/510305002/ Speaker Robin Vos took free trip to London with lobbyists and leaders from other states]\". ''Milwaukee Journal Sentinel'', April 12, 2018.</ref> Vos supports deregulating the payday loan industry.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> He opposes Medicaid expansion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wizmnews.com/2018/10/03/wisconsin-assembly-speaker-robin-vos-vows-to-never-take-medicaid-expansion-money/|title=Wisconsin Assembly Speaker Robin Vos vows to \u2018never\u2019 take Medicaid expansion money|date=2018-10-03|website=WIZM 92.3FM 1410AM|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 Vos endorsed [[Marco Rubio]] for president. After Rubio dropped out of the race, Vos endorsed [[Ted Cruz]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sommerhauser |first1=Mark |title=Robin Vos endorses Ted Cruz |url=http://host.madison.com/wsj/news/local/govt-and-politics/robin-vos-endorses-ted-cruz/article_a26b9134-af54-57fc-9c18-bd6230b9fff7.html|newspaper=Wisconsin State Journal |date=March 25, 2016 |accessdate=March 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019 Vos defended [[Brian Hagedorn]], a judge of the [[Wisconsin Court of Appeals]] running for a seat on the [[Wisconsin Supreme Court]], amid reports that Hagedorn had founded a school in 2016 that allowed for the expulsion of students and faculty if they were gay. Vos said he believed Hagedorn could rule fairly on LGBT issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/politics/2019/02/21/realtors-revoke-endorsement-supreme-court-candidate-after-reports-he-founded-school-allowed-expulsio/2936284002/|title=Realtors revoke endorsement of Supreme Court candidate Brian Hagedorn over school's policy on gay students|website=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|language=en|access-date=2019-03-01}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019 Vos was widely criticized for refusing to prohibit overnight floor sessions or allow paralyzed Democratic lawmaker [[Jimmy P. Anderson|Jimmy Anderson]], who is in a wheelchair, to phone into committee meetings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://madison.com/wsj/news/local/govt-and-politics/republicans-won-t-let-democratic-lawmaker-in-wheelchair-phone-in/article_4ce4e8b5-93e5-554c-8585-76b2ccef61d8.html|title=Republicans won't let Democratic lawmaker in wheelchair phone in|last=Associated Press|first=|date=1 August 2019|website=Wisconsin State Journal|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/politics/a28591321/wisconsin-lawmaker-wheelchair-robin-vos/|title=This Is Called Being a Colossal Dick for No Reason at All|last=Pierce|first=Charles P.|date=2 August 2019|website=Esquire|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He later accused Anderson of political grandstanding<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wisn.com/article/speaker-robin-vos-accuses-paralyzed-lawmaker-of-political-grandstanding/28583349|title=Assembly speaker accuses paralyzed lawmaker of 'political grandstanding'|last=Smith|first=Matt|date=1 August 2019|website=WISN 12 News|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and attempting to sabotage him as Vos took on his new national role as head of the National Conference of State Legislatures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/politics/2019/08/15/robin-vos-accuses-paralyzed-lawmaker-trying-sabotage-him/2018883001/|title=Robin Vos accuses paralyzed lawmaker of trying to sabotage him by seeking accommodations|last=Beck|first=Molly|date=15 August 2019|website=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019 Vos became the 47th President of the National Conference of State Legislatures.\n\nIn April 2020, amid the coronavirus pandemic, Vos opposed calls by Wisconsin Governor Tony Evers to delay an election from early April to late May, to make it a mail-in election, and to mail ballots to all registered voters.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/03/wisconsin-governor-makes-last-minute-plea-to-delay-tuesday-election-163441|title=Wisconsin governor makes last-minute plea to delay Tuesday election|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbc15.com/content/news/Wisconsin-GOP-says-election-should-go-on-as-scheduled-569361511.html|title=Wisconsin GOP says election should go on as scheduled|last=Danbeck|first=Associated Press, Jackson|website=www.nbc15.com|language=english|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> Due to the coronavirus pandemic, it was estimated that many voters would be effectively disenfranchised, and in-person voting was also considered a public health risk.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/03/wisconsin-vote-coronavirus-163931|title=\u2018It is terrifying\u2019: Wisconsin leaders warn of coronavirus disaster with Tuesday\u2019s vote|last=Montellaro|first=Zach|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> According to the ''[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]'', \"Vos had no answer to how local election officials are supposed to keep people safe as a massive shortage of poll workers has resulted in the closure or reduction of polling locations, forcing more people to vote at a single site.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/politics/elections/2020/04/03/tony-evers-calls-lawmakers-into-session-stop-person-voting/2940156001/|title=Republican lawmakers reject Wisconsin Gov. Tony Evers' call to stop in-person voting Tuesday because of virus threat|last=Beck|first=Molly|website=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> Vos said, \"If you are bored at home and sick of watching Netlfix, volunteer to go and help at the polls.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Curbing Evers administration ===\nAfter Democratic nominee [[Tony Evers]] won the [[2018 Wisconsin gubernatorial election]], defeating incumbent Republican governor Scott Walker, Vos was the first public official to propose curbing the incoming governor's powers.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/onpoint/2018/12/11/wisconsin-republicans-bill-power-grab-governor-tony-evers|title=What The Wisconsin Political Power Play Means For American Democracy|website=www.wbur.org|language=en|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref> He claimed it was to restore a balance of power between the governor and the legislature, despite having previously voted to expand gubernatorial power.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wbay.com/content/news/GOP-legislative-leaders-consider--499988532.html|title=Vos open to looking at ways to limit Evers\u2019 powers|last=BAUER|first=TODD RICHMOND and SCOTT|access-date=2018-11-10|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbc15.com/content/news/Vos-open-to-limiting-power-of-Evers-as-governor-499988291.html|title=Vos open to limiting power of Evers as governor|last=Press|first=Associated|access-date=2018-11-10|language=en}}</ref> Vos also said the changes were intended to lock in laws passed by Republicans and to prevent the incoming Democratic administration from fulfilling its campaign pledges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/12/wisconsin-gop-seeks-to-limit-democrat-everss-powers/577411/|title=\u2018Wisconsin Has Never Seen Anything Like This\u2019|last=Berman|first=Russell|date=2018-12-05|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-11}}</ref>\n\nChristopher Beem of the McCourtney Institute of Democracy at Pennsylvania State University described Wisconsin Republicans' power grab as a \"deeply undemocratic act.\" While it could be legal, Beem said, it erodes democratic norms: \"Wisconsin\u2019s GOP lawmakers are using power that the majority of the electorate has just taken away from them in order to make it more difficult for the incoming administration to undertake actions that the majority has just shown that it wants.\" Citing research by Harvard University political scientists Daniel Ziblatt and Steven Levitsky, Beem noted that \"democracy most often dies one little piece at a time. And the more lines are crossed, the more norms are spurned, the more perilous our situation becomes.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/wisconsin-gops-power-grab-is-a-danger-to-democracy-108543|title=Wisconsin GOP's power grab is a danger to democracy|last=Beem|first=Christopher|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref> In June 2019 the conservative majority on the Wisconsin Supreme Court rejected a challenge to the December 2018 laws, ruling that extraordinary sessions are constitutional.<ref>https://madison.com/ct/news/local/govt-and-politics/wisconsin-supreme-court-ruling-upholds-lame-duck-laws/article_3ca70585-a462-5faa-97c7-37b1e25543b9.html</ref>\n\n=== 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic ===\nIn April 2020, during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]], Vos opposed calls to delay Wisconsin's spring election and presidential primary election from early April to late May, to make it a mail-in election, and to mail ballots to all registered voters.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> In-person voting was considered a public health risk, and it was estimated that many voters would be effectively disenfranchised.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n\nOn election day, Vos served as an election inspector.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/07/politics/wisconsin-robin-vos-protective-gear/index.html|title=Republican Wisconsin assembly speaker wears protective gear while ironically telling voters they are 'incredibly safe to go out'|first=Kate |last=Sullivan|publisher=CNN|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> While \"dressed in head to toe PPE gear\",<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.businessinsider.com/wisconsin-gop-leader-says-voting-safe-dressed-ppe-gear-2020-4 |newspaper=[[Business Insider]] |title=Watch Wisconsin's Assembly Speaker tell voters it is 'incredibly safe to go out' while dressed in head to toe PPE gear |first=Grace |last=Panetta |date=April 7, 2020 |accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> he said it was \"incredibly safe\" to vote at the polls.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Electoral history ==\n\n{{Election box begin | title=Wisconsin 63rd District Assembly Election 2018}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Robin Vos\n  |votes      = 16,775\n  |percentage = 61.00%\n  |change     = -3.16%}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Joel Jacobsen\n  |votes      = 10,705\n  |percentage = 38.93%\n  |change     = +3.09%}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = \n  |candidate  = Write-ins\n  |votes      = 19\n  |percentage = 0.07%\n  |change     = }}\n{{Election box total\n  |votes      = '''27,499'''\n  |percentage = '''100.0%'''\n  |change     = '''-6.01%'''\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no swing|\n  |winner     = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin | title=Wisconsin 63rd District Assembly Election 2016}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Robin Vos\n  |votes      = 18,771\n  |percentage = 64.16%\n  |change     = +0.93%}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Andy Mitchell\n  |votes      = 10,487\n  |percentage = 35.84%\n  |change     = -0.86%}}\n{{Election box total\n  |votes      = '''29,258'''\n  |percentage = '''100.0%'''\n  |change     = '''+20.42%'''\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no swing|\n  |winner     = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin | title=Wisconsin 63rd District Assembly Election 2014}}\n{{Election 