s established in 2004]]\n[[Category:Political parties disestablished in 2016]]\n[[Category:2004 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2016 disestablishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Far-left politics in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Unreal7", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Respect_Party"}
{"title_page": "Balut (food)", "text_new": "{{short description|A developing bird embryo boiled and eaten from the shell}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:Inside a Balut - Embryo and Yolk.jpg|thumb|Partially [[egg shell|shelled]] balut [[egg (biology)|egg]] showing [[yolk]], baby chicken and veins running through it]]\n[[File:Anas platyrhynchos male female quadrat.jpg|thumb|[[Mallard ducks]] are used extensively in the production of balut\u2014female (left) and male (right)]]\n\n'''Balut''' ({{IPAc-en|b|\u0259|\u02c8|l|u\u02d0|t\n}} {{respell|b\u0259|LOOT}}, {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u0251\u02d0|l|u\u02d0|t\n}} {{respell|BAH|loot}};<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/balut|title=Definition of BALUT|website=www.merriam-webster.com|language=en|access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref> also spelled as '''balot''') is a fertilized [[Embryogenesis|developing]] egg [[embryo]] that is boiled and eaten from the shell. It is commonly sold as street food in the [[Philippines]] and other [[Southeast Asia|Southeast Asian]] countries.\n\nThe [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]] and [[Malay language|Malay]] word ''balot'' or ''balut'' means \"wrap\". The length of incubation before the egg is cooked is a matter of local preference, but generally ranges between 14 and 21 days.\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Balut egg.jpg|thumb|Veins in a freshly boiled, peeled balut egg]]\nA balut is a fertilized bird egg (usually a duck) which is incubated for a period of 14 to 21 days depending on the local culture and then boiled or steamed. The contents are eaten directly from the shell. Balut that is incubated for longer periods have a well-developed embryo and the features of the duckling are recognizable. The partially-developed embryo bones are soft enough to chew and swallow as a whole. The [[mallard]] duck (''Anas platyrhynchus''), also known as the \"Pateros duck\", is considered to be the most important breed for egg production to make balut.<ref name=\"Romjali\">{{cite journal |author1=Romjali, E.N. |author2=Lambio, A.L. |author3=Luis, E.S. |author4=Roxas, N.P. |author5=Barion, A.A.|year=2014|title= Fertility and hatchability of eggs on mallard ducks (Anas platyrhynchos L.) of different plumage pattern under different feeding regimes|journal=JITV|volume=19|issue=3|pages=674\u2013678}}</ref>\n\nBalut is common street food in the Philippines and other localities, and is also sold in stores and malls. It is a relatively cheap source of protein and calcium.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Eggs in Cookery: Proceedings of the Oxford Symposium of Food and Cookery 2006|last=Magat|first=Margaret|publisher=Prospect Books|year=2007|isbn=978-1-903018-54-5|editor-last=Hosking|editor-first=Richard|chapter='Balut,' the Fertilised Duck Eggs of the Philippines}}</ref> Balut was introduced to the Philippines by the Chinese around 1885 and since then, balut has been included as a traditional part of the culture.<ref name=\":1\"/> Wherever [[Filipinos]] migrated for work, a large market for balut would develop. Controversies arose as knowledge of the food spread around the Southeast Asian countries and then globally. People questioned the ethics of eating balut.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal|last=Magat|first=Margaret|date=January 1, 2002|title=Balut: \"Fertilized Duck Eggs and Their Role in Filipino Culture\"|jstor=1500289|journal=Western Folklore|volume=61|issue=1|pages=63\u201396|doi=10.2307/1500289 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n[[File:Balut Kambocyada bir yumurta cesidi.JPG|thumb|right|Balut in partially broken shells]]\n\n==Preparation==\n\n===Incubation===\n[[File:Balut .jpg|right|thumb|Closeup of balut after removing the shell]]\nTraditionally, the fertilized [[egg (biology)|eggs]] are incubated in the sun or buried in sand, and stored in baskets to retain warmth. In order for the embryo to develop normally, it must be exposed to heat for the correct period of time, while ensuring that the temperature is not too hot to harm the eggs or too cold to prevent growth.<ref name=\":2\">R. Ehrlich, Paul. \"Incubation: Heating Egg.\" Incubation: Heating Egg. Web. February 29, 2016.</ref> The embryo is very sensitive to high temperatures, and is easily killed upon cooking in the sun.<ref name=\":2\" /> After nine days, the eggs are held to a light to reveal the embryo inside. The production of balut depends on egg maturation cycles, where the egg begins developing and changes in texture. Throughout these various maturation periods, different temperatures are required to accentuate the specific egg and embryo characteristics. Within the first few stages of maturation, balut is known as \"balut sa puti\" (\"wrapped in white\") when it is white; the embryo inside is insufficiently developed to show a beak, feathers or claws, and the bones are undeveloped. These are made from very specific egg types, less than five days old and with no visible surface cracks.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal|author=Matejowsky, T.|year=2013|title=The incredible, edible balut. food, culture and society|journal=International Journal of Multidisciplinary Research|volume=16|issue=3|pages=387\u2013404}}</ref>\n\nThe duration of egg incubation is a matter of local preference. In the Philippines, balut is generally incubated for 14 to 18 days before being boiled for consumption. At about 14 to 16 days of incubation, the embryo floats on top of the egg white and yolk, and the balut is called \"mamatong\".<ref name=\":1\"/> The ideal balut is said to be 17 days old.\n\nThere are other versions of balut. In the Cambodian version, \"pong tia koun\", the egg is incubated for 18 to 20 days.  In the Vietnamese version, \"tr\u1ee9ng v\u1ecbt l\u1ed9n\", the egg is incubated for 19 to 21 days, when the embryo is old enough to be recognizable as a baby duck and has [[bone]]s that will be firm but tender when cooked. Some men prefer to eat an embryo that is much more developed, \"...so that it looks gross, because that is a way to prove your manhood.\"<ref name=\"Liedel\" /><ref name=\"revealed\">{{cite web |title=Cracking the shell: Balut revealed {{!}} Tangled Noodle |url=http://tanglednoodle.blogspot.ca/2011/03/cracking-shell-balut-revealed.html |website=tanglednoodle.blogspot.ca |date=March 13, 2011 |url-status=live |accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Chemistry of cooking ==\nDuring the cooking process, changes occur in the [[food chemistry]] of balut, such as the [[sol (colloid)|sol dispersion]] of water molecules within the embryonic fluid.<ref name=\":13\">{{cite web |url=http://wiki.ubc.ca/Course:FNH200/Lesson_02 |title=Course:FNH200/Lesson 02 - UBC Wiki |website=wiki.ubc.ca |accessdate=March 21, 2016}}</ref> This liquid becomes the broth for the solid which are parts of the duck within the egg. Although balut mainly consists of protein, fat is present and is emulsified within the fertilized embryo. After cooking, it can be considered a protein gel (depending on the length of time it was cooked). Heating high-protein food such as balut can cause the chemical changes to take place and fully or partially denature proteins, causing the surface to become thick and causing an irreversible gel protein to form.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nTemperature has a significant impact on the final taste and texture of the cooked balut. Warm temperatures of {{convert|29|-|30|C}} change the taste and texture of the yolk by making it more grainy. This can be attributed to the changes in proteins, and their partial denaturation, during the heating and incubation process.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |url=https://drive.google.com/folderview?id=0B-8ntUoE9iTtX1ZLcU1KVXAwOHM&usp=sharing_eid&invite=CJ6diZMN&ts=56be431a&usp=sharing_eid&urp=https://snt150.mail.live.com/?tid%253Dcm1bp-wMjR5RGw-g# |title=Redirecting... |website=drive.google.com |accessdate=March 17, 2016}}</ref> When boiling or cooking eggs, the white of the egg tends to solidify because the proteins are denatured in an irreversible reaction and turn from transparent to an opaque white.<ref>BBC. \"Cooking and Chemical Changes.\" BBC News. BBC, n.d. Web. February 29, 2016.</ref> Physical and chemical changes in the final balut product can also be attributed to microbial infections and the rate that microbes infect the balut at various stages.<ref name=\":3\" />\n[[File:Embryo egg of balut.jpg|thumb|Balut from Vancouver, British Columbia]]\n\nThere are many chemical changes that occur inside the duck egg as it is being processed, which can vary depending on how or what it is cooked with. While boiling, added salt can contribute to a number of chemical changes; it seems to increase the proportional weight of egg white within the shell, which can be due to the weight differences between the embryo and the egg white itself.<ref name=\":4\">Kaewmanee, Thammarat. \"Changes in Chemical Composition, Physical Properties and Microstructure of Duck Egg as Influenced by Salting.\" Research Gate. N.p., June 11, 2008. Web. February 29, 2016.</ref> Added salt can also increase the hardness of the egg yolk and affect the overall texture of the final balut product.<ref name=\":2\" /> Other chemical changes observed in nutrient content of the duck egg as it is processed are a slight decrease in the amount of available amino acids, water-soluble vitamins and minerals after the processing is complete.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Nutrition ==\n[[File:Balut eggs.jpg|right|thumb|Balut eggs]]There are different nutritional values for balut, since it can be either fertilized chicken or duck eggs.  Balut nutrition specifications between chicken and duck have minor differences, but both eggs have around 14 grams of crude protein, 188 calories each, and around 100 milligrams of calcium. A duck egg might have a higher value of nutrition than a chicken egg but overall, both chicken and duck balut have approximately the same nutritional value.<ref>Lambio, A. L. (2010). Poultry Production in the Tropics. Quezon, Diliman, Philippines: The University of Philippines Press.</ref>[[File:Egg minerlas.jpg|right|thumb|Nutrition specifications for egg-type duck (balut)]]\n[[File:Balut eggs nutrients.jpg|thumb|right|Nutrition specifications for egg-type chicken (balut)]]\n\n==Dishes and vending==\n[[File:15DayBalutEgg.png|thumb|left|Fifteen-day-old balut egg floating in a mixture of [[Hot sauce#Asia|hot sauce]] and [[vinegar]]]]\nIn the Philippines, balut eaters prefer salt, or a [[chili pepper|chili]], garlic, and vinegar (white or coconut sap) mixture to season their eggs.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://healthyeating.sfgate.com/balut-egg-2775.html|title= What Is a Balut Egg? | work=The San Francisco Chronicle\n}}</ref> The eggs are savored for their balance of textures and flavors; the broth surrounding the embryo is sipped from the egg before the shell is peeled, and the [[yolk]] and young chick inside can be eaten. All of the contents of the egg may be consumed, although the white albumen may remain uneaten depending on the age of the fertilized egg. This white albumen may have an unappetizing cartilaginous taste and is tough and rubbery in texture. In the [[Philippines]], balut have recently entered ''[[haute cuisine]]'' by being served as appetizers in restaurants, cooked [[adobo (Filipino cuisine)|adobo]] style, fried in [[omelette]]s or even used as filling in baked [[pastry|pastries]]. In Vietnam, balut is eaten with a pinch of pepper salt with lime/kumquat or ginger and rau r\u0103m (also known as [[laksa leaf]]). In Cambodia, balut is eaten while still warm in the shell and are served with nothing more than a little garnish, which is usually a mixture of lime juice and ground pepper.\n\n[[File:Chinese Balut sold in Nanjing 20100115.jpg|thumb|Shelled and fried balut]]\nA similar preparation is known in [[China]] as ''maodan'' ({{zh|c=\u6bdb\u86cb|p=m\u00e1o d\u00e0n|l=feathered egg}}), ''modan'' ({{zh|c=\u672b\u86cb|p=m\u00f2 d\u00e0n|l=end-stage egg}}), ''wangjidan''  ({{zh|c=\u65fa\u96de\u86cb|p=w\u00e0ng j\u012bd\u00e0n|l=flush egg}}) or ''huozhuzi''  ({{zh|c=\u6d3b\u73e0\u5b50|p=hu\u00f3zh\u016bzi|l=living bead}}). Chinese traders and migrants are said to have brought the idea of eating fertilized duck eggs to the Philippines. However, the knowledge and craft of balut-making has been localized by the balut-makers (''mangbabalot''). Today, balut production has not been [[mechanised agriculture|mechanized]] in favor of the traditional production by hand. \n\nVendors sell cooked balut from buckets of [[sand]] (used to retain warmth) accompanied by small packets of salt. Uncooked balut are rarely sold in Southeast Asia. In the [[United States]], [[Asian cuisine|Asian]] markets occasionally carry uncooked balut eggs. Alternatively, they can be ordered by mail. The cooking process is identical to that of hard-boiled chicken eggs, and baluts are eaten while still warm.\n\n[[File:BALUT.jpg|thumb|upright|Underaged balut with visible chick]]\nDuck eggs that are not properly developed after nine to twelve days are sold as ''penoy'', which look, smell and taste similar to a regular hard-boiled [[egg (food)|egg]]. In [[Filipino cuisine]], these are occasionally beaten and fried, similar to [[scrambled eggs]], and served with a [[vinegar]] dip.\n\n== Consumption and uses ==\n\n=== Locations of balut consumption ===\nBalut is consumed in high amounts within countries in Southeast Asia, including Laos, Cambodia, Vietnam, Thailand, and the Philippines.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite web |title=In Some Countries People Eat Balut(egg) fertilized duck embryo |year=2012 |url=http://www.unbelievable-facts.com/2012/07/in-some-countries-people-eat-balutegg.html |url-status=live |accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref> Pateros is a first-class municipality in Metro Manila, Philippines that is famous for its duck-raising industry and balut production.\n\nBalut is recognized as a national food of the Philippines, but possibly originated from China. It is said that an early form of balut was brought by Chinese traders and migrants to the Philippines; the Chinese may have sparked the interest and excitement for the Philippines' love of balut. It is commonly sold as a street food and served as an appetizer in restaurants. The taste of balut is similar to chicken soup. It has an unusual texture. \n\nBalut is found in some countries and locations of North America. While it cannot be found in every store in North America, specialty stores such as T&T, and in particular, Filipino stores in the Greater Vancouver area, often sell balut.<ref name=\":9\">{{cite web |title=Best balut in Vancouver. (n.d.) |url=http://www.yelp.ca/search?find_desc=balut |url-status=live |accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref> In the United States, growers such as Metzer Farms specialize in balut production, spreading the knowledge of balut and its awareness.\n\nA reason it may not be found or consumed as frequently in North America is that the majority of people outside of Southeast Asia still recognize balut as a novel and taboo food and often are anxious about trying it.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Consumption ===\nIn the Philippines, balut is often eaten with salt or a chili, garlic and vinegar (white or coconut sap) mixture to season, depending on personal preference.<ref name=\":11\">{{cite web |title=Balut: The Fertilized Duck Egg Street Snack - Modern Farmer |date=April 14, 2014 |author=Emily Liedel |url=http://modernfarmer.com/2014/04/balut-fertilized-duck-egg-street-snack/ |url-status=live |accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref> Balut can be served in many ways and may be cooked, boiled, and fried. It may be cooked adobo-style, fried in omelets, and used as filling in pastries.\n\nSome countries and locations will serve balut raw, although this is not a common practice. \"Raw,\" in this sense, could mean the balut was lightly boiled or cooked very briefly.<ref name=\":11\" /> This is potentially dangerous since it increases the risk of spoiling and of ingesting harmful microorganisms.<ref name=\":1\" />[[File:Balut Egg.jpg|thumb]]\n\nAlthough balut is globally recognized as a Filipino food, it is being consumed less and less in the Philippines.  This is partly due to increasingly Western tastes, but also because balut is often associated with poverty.<ref name=\"Liedel\">{{cite journal|author=Liedel, E.|date=April 14, 2014|title=Balut: The fertilized duck egg street snack|journal=Modern Farmer}}</ref>\n\n== Incubation and storage ==\n[[File:Purchased Balut Egg .jpg|thumb|Balut egg purchased from Vancouver supermarket, with different labeling requirements than traditional chicken eggs]]\n \nBalut is considered to be a street food, and as with many street foods, balut should be eaten as soon as it is prepared. Sources suggest that at most, the shelf-life of a cooked balut is one day, but can be kept in the refrigerator for up to one week.<ref name=Century>{{cite web |url=http://www.fftc.agnet.org/library.php?func=view&style=&type_id=7&id=20110716205807&print=1 |title=Enhancing the value of eggs: How to make balut and century eggs |website=www.fftc.agnet.org |url-status=live |accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the FDA Food Code, balut can perish over time or due to temperature changes. After being cooked, balut should be handled either at {{Convert|57|C}} and above, or kept at or below {{Convert|5|C}}.<ref name=\":14\"/>\n\nWhile most countries have specific regulations and standards for food, Canada has certain egg regulations pertaining to what products can be labelled as an egg.  Balut eggs are not subjected to the egg regulations in Canada under the Canadian Food Inspection Agency, meaning they do not require the specific labeling requirements and rules of the traditional chicken egg.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite journal|date=March 3, 2016 |title=Balut |journal=CPHAZ |url=http://www.myhealthunit.ca/en/partnerandhealthproviderresources/resources/EH-Food_Safety_Fact_Sheets_-_Specialty_Foods_BALUT.pdf |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404094507/http://www.myhealthunit.ca/en/partnerandhealthproviderresources/resources/EH-Food_Safety_Fact_Sheets_-_Specialty_Foods_BALUT.pdf|archivedate=April 4, 2016 |accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref>[[File:Balut stall by Ilpo's Sojourn in Eagle Rock, California.jpg|thumb|Balut stall]]\n\n== Controversies ==\n\n===Religion===\nEating balut is forbidden for some religious groups. Both Judaism and Islam have strict prohibitions on consuming food that is prepared in manners incompatible with religiously-prescribed dietary laws. In [[Judaism]], the embryo of a chick inside an egg of a bird, even a kosher bird, is forbidden for consumption.<ref>[http://www.jewishpress.com/judaism/torah/kosher-and-non-kosher-eggs/2011/11/12/ Kosher And Non-Kosher Eggs] Jewish Press. Retrieved December 4, 2018.</ref>  The [[Quran]] forbids consumption of meat if the animal has not been slaughtered properly, making the animal or animal-product \"maytah\".<ref name=Century/><ref name=\":6\" /> Because balut is an egg containing a partly-developed embryo,<ref>Tang, Q., Li-Chan, E. C. Y., Byrne, S. K., & Cheng, K. M. (n.d.). Effect of storage temperature on sensory and microbiological quality of duck balut eggs, 4.</ref> this makes it \"[[haram]]\", or \"forbidden\".<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web |title=Is eating egg haram / makruh - Multaqa Ahl al-Hadeeth |date=August 28, 2011 |url=http://www.ahlalhdeeth.com/vbe/showthread.php?t=13636 |url-status=live |accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fda.gov/Food/GuidanceRegulation/RetailFoodProtection/FoodCode/ucm189170.htm |title=Food Code - FDA Food Code 2009: Annex 3 - Public Health Reasons / Administrative Guidelines - Chapter 1, Purpose and Definitions |last=Nutrition |first=Center for Food Safety and Applied |website=www.fda.gov |language=en |accessdate=March 20, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/health/2011/09/12/eating-balut-going-too-far.html|title=Eating Balut: Going Too Far? {{!}} Fox News |last=Kilham |first=Chris |date=September 15, 2011 |website=Fox News |language=en-US |url-status=live |accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Christianity]],  the [[Members Church of God International]] forbids their members to eat \"balut\" for it is written in [https://biblehub.com/acts/15-20.htm Acts 15:20],\n\"But that we write unto them, that they abstain from pollutions of idols, and ''from'' fornication, and ''from'' things strangled, and ''from'' blood.\"\n\nAccording to them,  the word \"strangled\" refers to those animals who died without pouring its blood upon the ground as written in [https://biblehub.com/deuteronomy/15-23.htm Deut. 15:23].\n\n\"Only thou shalt not eat the blood thereof; thou shalt pour it upon the ground as water.\"\n\n===Animal welfare===\nInformation relating to whether boiling a partially-developed embryo is ethically acceptable or not can be found in the legislation relating to the euthanasia and treatment of research animals. Bird embryos that have reached greater than 50% of their incubation have developed a [[neural tube]] sufficient for pain perception; therefore, they should be euthanized by similar methods used in avian neonates such as anesthetic overdose, decapitation, or prolonged exposure to [[carbon dioxide]].<ref name=\"AVMA\">{{cite web|title=AVMA Guidelines for the Euthanasia of Animals - 2013 edition |date=2013 |author=Leary, S. |url=https://www.avma.org/KB/Policies/Documents/euthanasia.pdf|accessdate=March 24, 2016 |publisher=AVMA|display-authors=etal}}</ref> Similarly, in the UK, embryonic birds are \"protected animals\" once they have reached the last third of their incubation period.<ref name=\"Aspa\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/consolidated-version-of-aspa-1986 |publisher=Home Office (UK) |title=Consolidated version of ASPA 1986 |year=2014 |accessdate=March 24, 2016}}</ref> There are specified methods of humanely killing protected animals used in research, but boiling is not one of these.  Depending on the species of duck, some eggs used for balut would be boiled within the last half or third of embryo development. Duck embryos are often taken off incubation in order to stunt the growth process, the embryos no longer develop, and becomes readily available for purchasing. The [[RSPCA Australia]] recommends against boiling the duck embryo from the 18th day of incubation onwards due to the potential for suffering beyond that point, and notes that it is \"an area that is yet to be further researched\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Is the practice of boiling pre-hatched duck embryos in their shell humane?|url=http://kb.rspca.org.au/Is-the-practice-of-boiling-pre-hatched-duck-embryos-in-their-shell-humane_511.html|website=RSPCA Australia knowledgebase|accessdate=October 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nSeveral groups wish to ban balut.<ref>Matejowsky, T. (2013). The Incredible, Edible Balut. Food, Culture and Society: An International Journal of Multidisciplinary Research, 16(3), 387\u2013404.</ref> A petition has been raised to get 5,000 signatures to have balut labeled \"fertilized duck egg with embryo\" and taken off the menu in the Maharlika restaurant, New York.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=http://kickerdaily.com/animal-rights-activist-stop-balut-serving-in-new-york/|title=Animal rights activist: Stop serving 'balut' in New York|website=Kicker Daily News|language=en-us|accessdate=March 20, 2016|date=April 13, 2015|author=San Jose, C.E.}}</ref> {{As of|2014}}, the restaurant was selling balut for $5 each.<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite web |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/02/05/travel/how-to-eat-balut/|publisher=CNN|year=2014|accessdate=March 24, 2016|title=Balut: The Filipino delicacy that makes the world squirm |author=Calderon, J.}}</ref> As a response to this petition, Filipino New Yorkers have created a counter petition asking to leave the food item alone.<ref name=\":7\"/>\n\n===Health===\nThe incubation temperatures and environment required for the proper development of balut during processing are ideal growth conditions for many bacteria including ''[[Salmonella enteritidis]]''. In addition, faecal [[pathogen]]s can be deposited on the egg shell surface during laying. Balut is therefore labelled as a \"Hazardous Food\" in Canada.<ref name=\":142\" /> Warnings have been published to obtain balut only from safe, well-known producers.<ref name=\":142\">{{cite web |author=Information Sheet |publisher=University of Guelph |date=2011 |title=Balut |url=http://www.myhealthunit.ca/en/partnerandhealthproviderresources/resources/EH-Food_Safety_Fact_Sheets_-_Specialty_Foods_BALUT.pdf |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404094507/http://www.myhealthunit.ca/en/partnerandhealthproviderresources/resources/EH-Food_Safety_Fact_Sheets_-_Specialty_Foods_BALUT.pdf |archive-date=April 4, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Outside Southeast Asia ==\nOutside of Southeast Asia, balut is often considered a novelty or [[taboo food]] that has been featured on reality television shows, such as in season 1 of ''[[Bizarre Foods with Andrew Zimmern]]'', or as part of eating challenges, such as on ''[[Fear Factor]]'' in 2002, ''[[Hell's Kitchen (American TV series)|Hell's Kitchen]]'' in 2013, ''[[The Amazing Race Asia 2]]'', ''[[The Amazing Race Australia 2]]'', ''[[Velyki Perehony|The Amazing Race Ukraine]]'', ''[[Survivor: Palau]]'', ''[[Survivor: China]]'', ''[[Survivor: Caramoan]]'', ''[[Survivor: Cambodia]]'', and ''[[Good Mythical Morning]]''.<ref>[http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2013/04/survivor-caramoan-its-corinne-vs-phillip-when-the-tribes-merge.html 'Survivor: Caramoan': It's Corinne vs. Phillip when the tribes merge]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/lifestyle/08/05/13/balut-gets-spotlight-new-york |title= Balut gets spotlight in New York}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, the eggs are sold at Asian markets. However, to get the right age eggs and to ensure freshness, it is recommended {{by whom|date=March 2016}} that they be purchased from a professional or an egg vendor at Asian farmers markets.\n\n[[Phillipe Nover]] of Team Nogueira ate balut during [[The Ultimate Fighter: Team Nogueira vs. Team Mir|Season 8]] of ''[[The Ultimate Fighter]]'', encouraging his teammates to do the same.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/2008/11/episode-no-8-recap-the-ultimate-fighter-team-nogueira-vs-team-mir |title= Episode No. 8 recap: \"The Ultimate Fighter: Team Nogueira vs. Team Mir\"}}</ref>{{relevance inline|date=January 2018}}\n\n==Folk medicine==\nAccording to popular Vietnamese belief, these eggs are a nutritious and restorative food for pregnant or delivering women.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n==Guinness World Record==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Townsfolk eating Balut - April 2015.jpg|thumb|upright=1.0|alt=Pateros citizens eating largest serving of balut|\t\nA huge crowd joined and witnessed the boodle fight of cooked rice with adobong ''balut''.]] -->\nOn April 10, 2015, former Pateros mayor [[Jaime \"Joey\" C. Medina]] collaborated with [[Center for Culinary Arts, Manila|Center for Culinary Arts (CCA, Manila)]] and [[History Channel|History (U.S. TV network)]] to attempt to set the record for the world's largest serving of balut. The CCA chefs, headed by Chef Tristan Encarnacion, prepared 1,000 pieces of balut into an adobo dish that was recorded to have weighed 117.5 kilograms. The resulting dish was enjoyed by the townsfolk in a symbolic [[boodle fight]], with tables topped with banana leaves stretching along B. Morcilla Street.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cnnphilippines.com/lifestyle/2015/04/12/philippines-in-world-record-attempt-for-largest-serving-of-balut.html |title=Philippines in world record attempt for largest serving of balut |publisher=CNN Philippines |date=April 14, 2015 |access-date=April 26, 2018}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/lifestyle/04/10/15/pateros-eyes-world-record-attempt-balut |title=Pateros eyes world record attempt for balut |publisher=ABS-CBN News |date=April 11, 2015 |access-date=April 27, 2018}}</ref>\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Pateros History Maker Award.jpg|thumb|right|alt=History Maker Award Joey Medina|The ''History Maker Award'' being held by Mr. Liza Morales ''(left)'' and Mayor Joey Medina ''(right)'']] -->\n\nThe record was later awarded to [[Pateros, Metro Manila]] and to this date, the record still stands.\n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/375333-largest-serving-of-balut |title=Largest serving of balut |publisher=Guinness World Records |date=April 10, 2015 |access-date=April 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Food}}\n{{div col}}\n* {{annotated link|Balut (game)}}\n* {{annotated link|Century egg}}\n* {{annotated link|Isaw}}\n* {{annotated link|Ngo_hiang|Kikiam}}\n* {{annotated link|Kutti pi}}\n* {{annotated link|Delicacy#Delicacies|List of delicacies}}\n* {{annotated link|Salted duck egg}}\n* {{annotated link|Smoked egg}}\n* {{annotated link|Soy egg}}\n* {{annotated link|Tea egg}}\n* {{annotated link|Tokneneng|Kwek-Kwek}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite encyclopedia |last=Davidson |first=Alan |authorlink=Alan Davidson (food writer) |encyclopedia=[[Oxford Companion to Food]] |title=Balut |year=1999 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=0-19-211579-0 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/oxfordcompaniont00davi_0/page/53 53] |url=https://archive.org/details/oxfordcompaniont00davi_0/page/53 }}\n\nMagat, Margaret (2019). Balut: Fertilized Eggs and the Making of Culinary Capital in the Filipino Diaspora, by Bloomsbury Academic, Nov. 2019. *[https://www.bloomsburycollections.com/book/balut-fertilized-eggs-and-the-making-of-culinary-capital-in-the-filipino-diaspora/]\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Balut}}\n* [http://www.accessexcellence.org/AE/ATG/data/released/0272-JacquelynWesolosky/  How to make the Hawaiian version of Balut]\n* [http://www.lemanger.fr/index.php/ethnology/balut-the-ugly-duckling-embryo/?lang=en Balut : the ugly duckling embryo] : The balut in Filipino culture\n* [http://www.foxnews.com/health/2011/09/12/eating-balut-going-too-far/ Eating Balut: Going Too Far?]\n* [http://healthyeating.sfgate.com/balut-egg-2775.html What is a Balut Egg?]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150414014714/http://vietworldkitchen.typepad.com/blog/2008/01/half-hatched-du.html Half-hatched Duck Eggs: Hot Vit Lon]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NCsa_Doev7Y How To Eat Balut -- The Strangest Food You Can Buy In New York City on YouTube]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rZPWYAEksHk Balut | The filipino food delicacy, a fertilized duck egg on YouTube]\n\n{{Eggs}}\n\n[[Category:Chinese cuisine]]\n[[Category:Egg dishes]]\n[[Category:Philippine cuisine]]\n[[Category:Tagalog words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Thai cuisine]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese cuisine]]\n[[Category:Street food in the Philippines]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|A developing bird embryo boiled and eaten from the shell}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:Inside a Balut - Embryo and Yolk.jpg|thumb|Partially [[egg shell|shelled]] balut [[egg (biology)|egg]] showing [[yolk]], baby chicken and veins running through it]]\n[[File:Anas platyrhynchos male female quadrat.jpg|thumb|[[Mallard ducks]] are used extensively in the production of balut\u2014female (left) and male (right)]]\n\n'''Balut''' ({{IPAc-en|b|\u0259|\u02c8|l|u\u02d0|t\n}} {{respell|b\u0259|LOOT}}, {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u0251\u02d0|l|u\u02d0|t\n}} {{respell|BAH|loot}};<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/balut|title=Definition of BALUT|website=www.merriam-webster.com|language=en|access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref> also spelled as '''balot''') is a fertilized [[Embryogenesis|developing]] egg [[embryo]] that is boiled and eaten from the shell. It is commonly sold as street food in the [[Philippines]] and other [[Southeast Asia|Southeast Asian]] countries.\n\nThe [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]] and [[Malay language|Malay]] word ''balot'' or ''balut'' means \"wrap\". The length of incubation before the egg is cooked is a matter of local preference, but generally ranges between 14 and 21 days.\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Balut egg.jpg|thumb|Veins in a freshly boiled, peeled balut egg]]\nA balut is a fertilized bird egg (usually a duck) which is incubated for a period of 14 to 21 days depending on the local culture and then boiled or steamed. The contents are eaten directly from the shell. Balut that is incubated for longer periods have a well-developed embryo and the features of the duckling are recognizable. The partially-developed embryo bones are soft enough to chew and swallow as a whole. The [[mallard]] duck (''Anas platyrhynchus''), also known as the \"Pateros duck\", is considered to be the most important breed for egg production to make balut.<ref name=\"Romjali\">{{cite journal |author1=Romjali, E.N. |author2=Lambio, A.L. |author3=Luis, E.S. |author4=Roxas, N.P. |author5=Barion, A.A.|year=2014|title= Fertility and hatchability of eggs on mallard ducks (Anas platyrhynchos L.) of different plumage pattern under different feeding regimes|journal=JITV|volume=19|issue=3|pages=674\u2013678}}</ref>\n\nBalut is common street food in the Philippines and other localities, and is also sold in stores and malls. It is a relatively cheap source of protein and calcium.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Eggs in Cookery: Proceedings of the Oxford Symposium of Food and Cookery 2006|last=Magat|first=Margaret|publisher=Prospect Books|year=2007|isbn=978-1-903018-54-5|editor-last=Hosking|editor-first=Richard|chapter='Balut,' the Fertilised Duck Eggs of the Philippines}}</ref> Balut was introduced to the Philippines by the Chinese around 1885 and since then, balut has been included as a traditional part of the culture.<ref name=\":1\"/> Wherever [[Filipinos]] migrated for work, a large market for balut would develop. Controversies arose as knowledge of the food spread around the Southeast Asian countries and then globally. People questioned the ethics of eating balut.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal|last=Magat|first=Margaret|date=January 1, 2002|title=Balut: \"Fertilized Duck Eggs and Their Role in Filipino Culture\"|jstor=1500289|journal=Western Folklore|volume=61|issue=1|pages=63\u201396|doi=10.2307/1500289 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n[[File:Balut Kambocyada bir yumurta cesidi.JPG|thumb|right|Balut in partially broken shells]]\n\n==Preparation==\n\n===Incubation===\n[[File:Balut .jpg|right|thumb|Closeup of balut after removing the shell]]\nTraditionally, the fertilized [[egg (biology)|eggs]] are incubated in the sun or buried in sand, and stored in baskets to retain warmth. In order for the embryo to develop normally, it must be exposed to heat for the correct period of time, while ensuring that the temperature is not too hot to harm the eggs or too cold to prevent growth.<ref name=\":2\">R. Ehrlich, Paul. \"Incubation: Heating Egg.\" Incubation: Heating Egg. Web. February 29, 2016.</ref> The embryo is very sensitive to high temperatures, and is easily killed upon cooking in the sun.<ref name=\":2\" /> After nine days, the eggs are held to a light to reveal the embryo inside. The production of balut depends on egg maturation cycles, where the egg begins developing and changes in texture. Throughout these various maturation periods, different temperatures are required to accentuate the specific egg and embryo characteristics. Within the first few stages of maturation, balut is known as \"balut sa puti\" (\"wrapped in white\") when it is white; the embryo inside is insufficiently developed to show a beak, feathers or claws, and the bones are undeveloped. These are made from very specific egg types, less than five days old and with no visible surface cracks.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal|author=Matejowsky, T.|year=2013|title=The incredible, edible balut. food, culture and society|journal=International Journal of Multidisciplinary Research|volume=16|issue=3|pages=387\u2013404}}</ref>\n\nThe duration of egg incubation is a matter of local preference. In the Philippines, balut is generally incubated for 14 to 18 days before being boiled for consumption. At about 14 to 16 days of incubation, the embryo floats on top of the egg white and yolk, and the balut is called \"mamatong\".<ref name=\":1\"/> The ideal balut is said to be 17 days old.\n\nThere are other versions of balut. In the Cambodian version, \"pong tia koun\", the egg is incubated for 18 to 20 days.  In the Vietnamese version, \"tr\u1ee9ng v\u1ecbt l\u1ed9n\", the egg is incubated for 19 to 21 days, when the embryo is old enough to be recognizable as a baby duck and has [[bone]]s that will be firm but tender when cooked. Some men prefer to eat an embryo that is much more developed, \"...so that it looks gross, because that is a way to prove your manhood.\"<ref name=\"Liedel\" /><ref name=\"revealed\">{{cite web |title=Cracking the shell: Balut revealed {{!}} Tangled Noodle |url=http://tanglednoodle.blogspot.ca/2011/03/cracking-shell-balut-revealed.html |website=tanglednoodle.blogspot.ca |date=March 13, 2011 |url-status=live |accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Chemistry of cooking ==\nDuring the cooking process, changes occur in the [[food chemistry]] of balut, such as the [[sol (colloid)|sol dispersion]] of water molecules within the embryonic fluid.<ref name=\":13\">{{cite web |url=http://wiki.ubc.ca/Course:FNH200/Lesson_02 |title=Course:FNH200/Lesson 02 - UBC Wiki |website=wiki.ubc.ca |accessdate=March 21, 2016}}</ref> This liquid becomes the broth for the solid which are parts of the duck within the egg. Although balut mainly consists of protein, fat is present and is emulsified within the fertilized embryo. After cooking, it can be considered a protein gel (depending on the length of time it was cooked). Heating high-protein food such as balut can cause the chemical changes to take place and fully or partially denature proteins, causing the surface to become thick and causing an irreversible gel protein to form.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nTemperature has a significant impact on the final taste and texture of the cooked balut. Warm temperatures of {{convert|29|-|30|C}} change the taste and texture of the yolk by making it more grainy. This can be attributed to the changes in proteins, and their partial denaturation, during the heating and incubation process.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |url=https://drive.google.com/folderview?id=0B-8ntUoE9iTtX1ZLcU1KVXAwOHM&usp=sharing_eid&invite=CJ6diZMN&ts=56be431a&usp=sharing_eid&urp=https://snt150.mail.live.com/?tid%253Dcm1bp-wMjR5RGw-g# |title=Redirecting... |website=drive.google.com |accessdate=March 17, 2016}}</ref> When boiling or cooking eggs, the white of the egg tends to solidify because the proteins are denatured in an irreversible reaction and turn from transparent to an opaque white.<ref>BBC. \"Cooking and Chemical Changes.\" BBC News. BBC, n.d. Web. February 29, 2016.</ref> Physical and chemical changes in the final balut product can also be attributed to microbial infections and the rate that microbes infect the balut at various stages.<ref name=\":3\" />\n[[File:Embryo egg of balut.jpg|thumb|Balut from Vancouver, British Columbia]]\n\nThere are many chemical changes that occur inside the duck egg as it is being processed, which can vary depending on how or what it is cooked with. While boiling, added salt can contribute to a number of chemical changes; it seems to increase the proportional weight of egg white within the shell, which can be due to the weight differences between the embryo and the egg white itself.<ref name=\":4\">Kaewmanee, Thammarat. \"Changes in Chemical Composition, Physical Properties and Microstructure of Duck Egg as Influenced by Salting.\" Research Gate. N.p., June 11, 2008. Web. February 29, 2016.</ref> Added salt can also increase the hardness of the egg yolk and affect the overall texture of the final balut product.<ref name=\":2\" /> Other chemical changes observed in nutrient content of the duck egg as it is processed are a slight decrease in the amount of available amino acids, water-soluble vitamins and minerals after the processing is complete.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Nutrition ==\n[[File:Balut eggs.jpg|right|thumb|Balut eggs]]There are different nutritional values for balut, since it can be either fertilized chicken or duck eggs.  Balut nutrition specifications between chicken and duck have minor differences, but both eggs have around 14 grams of crude protein, 188 calories each, and around 100 milligrams of calcium. A duck egg might have a higher value of nutrition than a chicken egg but overall, both chicken and duck balut have approximately the same nutritional value.<ref>Lambio, A. L. (2010). Poultry Production in the Tropics. Quezon, Diliman, Philippines: The University of Philippines Press.</ref>[[File:Egg minerlas.jpg|right|thumb|Nutrition specifications for egg-type duck (balut)]]\n[[File:Balut eggs nutrients.jpg|thumb|right|Nutrition specifications for egg-type chicken (balut)]]\n\n==Dishes and vending==\n[[File:15DayBalutEgg.png|thumb|left|Fifteen-day-old balut egg floating in a mixture of [[Hot sauce#Asia|hot sauce]] and [[vinegar]]]]\nIn the Philippines, balut eaters prefer salt, or a [[chili pepper|chili]], garlic, and vinegar (white or coconut sap) mixture to season their eggs.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://healthyeating.sfgate.com/balut-egg-2775.html|title= What Is a Balut Egg? | work=The San Francisco Chronicle\n}}</ref> The eggs are savored for their balance of textures and flavors; the broth surrounding the embryo is sipped from the egg before the shell is peeled, and the [[yolk]] and young chick inside can be eaten. All of the contents of the egg may be consumed, although the white albumen may remain uneaten depending on the age of the fertilized egg. This white albumen may have an unappetizing cartilaginous taste and is tough and rubbery in texture. In the [[Philippines]], balut have recently entered ''[[haute cuisine]]'' by being served as appetizers in restaurants, cooked [[adobo (Filipino cuisine)|adobo]] style, fried in [[omelette]]s or even used as filling in baked [[pastry|pastries]]. In Vietnam, balut is eaten with a pinch of pepper salt with lime/kumquat or ginger and rau r\u0103m (also known as [[laksa leaf]]). In Cambodia, balut is eaten while still warm in the shell and are served with nothing more than a little garnish, which is usually a mixture of lime juice and ground pepper.\n\n[[File:Chinese Balut sold in Nanjing 20100115.jpg|thumb|Shelled and fried balut]]\nA similar preparation is known in [[China]] as ''maodan'' ({{zh|c=\u6bdb\u86cb|p=m\u00e1o d\u00e0n|l=feathered egg}}), ''modan'' ({{zh|c=\u672b\u86cb|p=m\u00f2 d\u00e0n|l=end-stage egg}}), ''wangjidan''  ({{zh|c=\u65fa\u96de\u86cb|p=w\u00e0ng j\u012bd\u00e0n|l=flush egg}}) or ''huozhuzi''  ({{zh|c=\u6d3b\u73e0\u5b50|p=hu\u00f3zh\u016bzi|l=living bead}}). Chinese traders and migrants are said to have brought the idea of eating fertilized duck eggs to the Philippines. However, the knowledge and craft of balut-making has been localized by the balut-makers (''mangbabalot''). Today, balut production has not been [[mechanised agriculture|mechanized]] in favor of the traditional production by hand. \n\nVendors sell cooked balut from buckets of [[sand]] (used to retain warmth) accompanied by small packets of salt. Uncooked balut are rarely sold in Southeast Asia. In the [[United States]], [[Asian cuisine|Asian]] markets occasionally carry uncooked balut eggs. Alternatively, they can be ordered by mail. The cooking process is identical to that of hard-boiled chicken eggs, and baluts are eaten while still warm.\n\n[[File:BALUT.jpg|thumb|upright|Underaged balut with visible chick]]\nDuck eggs that are not properly developed after nine to twelve days are sold as ''penoy'', which look, smell and taste similar to a regular hard-boiled [[egg (food)|egg]]. In [[Filipino cuisine]], these are occasionally beaten and fried, similar to [[scrambled eggs]], and served with a [[vinegar]] dip.\n\n== Consumption and uses ==\n\n=== Locations of balut consumption ===\nBalut is consumed in high amounts within countries in Southeast Asia, including Laos, Cambodia, Vietnam, Thailand, and the Philippines.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite web |title=In Some Countries People Eat Balut(egg) fertilized duck embryo |year=2012 |url=http://www.unbelievable-facts.com/2012/07/in-some-countries-people-eat-balutegg.html |url-status=live |accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref> Pateros is a first-class municipality in Metro Manila, Philippines that is famous for its duck-raising industry and balut production.\n\nBalut is recognized as a national food of the Philippines, but possibly originated from China. It is said that an early form of balut was brought by Chinese traders and migrants to the Philippines; the Chinese may have sparked the interest and excitement for the Philippines' love of balut. It is commonly sold as a street food and served as an appetizer in restaurants. The taste of balut is similar to chicken soup. It has an unusual texture. \n\nBalut is found in some countries and locations of North America. While it cannot be found in every store in North America, specialty stores such as T&T, and in particular, Filipino stores in the Greater Vancouver area, often sell balut.<ref name=\":9\">{{cite web |title=Best balut in Vancouver. (n.d.) |url=http://www.yelp.ca/search?find_desc=balut |url-status=live |accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref> In the United States, growers such as Metzer Farms specialize in balut production, spreading the knowledge of balut and its awareness.\n\nA reason it may not be found or consumed as frequently in North America is that the majority of people outside of Southeast Asia still recognize balut as a novel and taboo food and often are anxious about trying it.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Consumption ===\nIn the Philippines, balut is often eaten with salt or a chili, garlic and vinegar (white or coconut sap) mixture to season, depending on personal preference.<ref name=\":11\">{{cite web |title=Balut: The Fertilized Duck Egg Street Snack - Modern Farmer |date=April 14, 2014 |author=Emily Liedel |url=http://modernfarmer.com/2014/04/balut-fertilized-duck-egg-street-snack/ |url-status=live |accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref> Balut can be served in many ways and may be cooked, boiled, and fried. It may be cooked adobo-style, fried in omelets, and used as filling in pastries.\n\nSome countries and locations will serve balut raw, although this is not a common practice. \"Raw,\" in this sense, could mean the balut was lightly boiled or cooked very briefly.<ref name=\":11\" /> This is potentially dangerous since it increases the risk of spoiling and of ingesting harmful microorganisms.<ref name=\":1\" />[[File:Balut Egg.jpg|thumb]]\n\nAlthough balut is globally recognized as a Filipino food, it is being consumed less and less in the Philippines.  This is partly due to increasingly Western tastes, but also because balut is often associated with poverty.<ref name=\"Liedel\">{{cite journal|author=Liedel, E.|date=April 14, 2014|title=Balut: The fertilized duck egg street snack|journal=Modern Farmer}}</ref>\n\n== Incubation and storage ==\n[[File:Purchased Balut Egg .jpg|thumb|Balut egg purchased from Vancouver supermarket, with different labeling requirements than traditional chicken eggs]]\n \nBalut is considered to be a street food, and as with many street foods, balut should be eaten as soon as it is prepared. Sources suggest that at most, the shelf-life of a cooked balut is one day, but can be kept in the refrigerator for up to one week.<ref name=Century>{{cite web |url=http://www.fftc.agnet.org/library.php?func=view&style=&type_id=7&id=20110716205807&print=1 |title=Enhancing the value of eggs: How to make balut and century eggs |website=www.fftc.agnet.org |url-status=live |accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the FDA Food Code, balut can perish over time or due to temperature changes. After being cooked, balut should be handled either at {{Convert|57|C}} and above, or kept at or below {{Convert|5|C}}.<ref name=\":14\"/>\n\nWhile most countries have specific regulations and standards for food, Canada has certain egg regulations pertaining to what products can be labelled as an egg.  Balut eggs are not subjected to the egg regulations in Canada under the Canadian Food Inspection Agency, meaning they do not require the specific labeling requirements and rules of the traditional chicken egg.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite journal|date=March 3, 2016 |title=Balut |journal=CPHAZ |url=http://www.myhealthunit.ca/en/partnerandhealthproviderresources/resources/EH-Food_Safety_Fact_Sheets_-_Specialty_Foods_BALUT.pdf |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404094507/http://www.myhealthunit.ca/en/partnerandhealthproviderresources/resources/EH-Food_Safety_Fact_Sheets_-_Specialty_Foods_BALUT.pdf|archivedate=April 4, 2016 |accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref>[[File:Balut stall by Ilpo's Sojourn in Eagle Rock, California.jpg|thumb|Balut stall]]\n\n== Controversies ==\n\n===Religion===\nEating balut is forbidden for some religious groups. Both Judaism and Islam have strict prohibitions on consuming food that is prepared in manners incompatible with religiously proscribed dietary laws. In [[Judaism]], the embryo of a chick inside an egg of a bird, even a kosher bird, is forbidden for consumption.<ref>[http://www.jewishpress.com/judaism/torah/kosher-and-non-kosher-eggs/2011/11/12/ Kosher And Non-Kosher Eggs] Jewish Press. Retrieved December 4, 2018.</ref>  The [[Quran]] forbids consumption of meat if the animal has not been slaughtered properly, making the animal or animal-product \"maytah\".<ref name=Century/><ref name=\":6\" /> Because balut is an egg containing a partly-developed embryo,<ref>Tang, Q., Li-Chan, E. C. Y., Byrne, S. K., & Cheng, K. M. (n.d.). Effect of storage temperature on sensory and microbiological quality of duck balut eggs, 4.</ref> this makes it \"[[haram]]\", or \"forbidden\".<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web |title=Is eating egg haram / makruh - Multaqa Ahl al-Hadeeth |date=August 28, 2011 |url=http://www.ahlalhdeeth.com/vbe/showthread.php?t=13636 |url-status=live |accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fda.gov/Food/GuidanceRegulation/RetailFoodProtection/FoodCode/ucm189170.htm |title=Food Code - FDA Food Code 2009: Annex 3 - Public Health Reasons / Administrative Guidelines - Chapter 1, Purpose and Definitions |last=Nutrition |first=Center for Food Safety and Applied |website=www.fda.gov |language=en |accessdate=March 20, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/health/2011/09/12/eating-balut-going-too-far.html|title=Eating Balut: Going Too Far? {{!}} Fox News |last=Kilham |first=Chris |date=September 15, 2011 |website=Fox News |language=en-US |url-status=live |accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Christianity]],  the [[Members Church of God International]] forbids their members to eat \"balut\" for it is written in [https://biblehub.com/acts/15-20.htm Acts 15:20],\n\"But that we write unto them, that they abstain from pollutions of idols, and ''from'' fornication, and ''from'' things strangled, and ''from'' blood.\"\n\nAccording to them,  the word \"strangled\" refers to those animals who died without pouring its blood upon the ground as written in [https://biblehub.com/deuteronomy/15-23.htm Deut. 15:23].\n\n\"Only thou shalt not eat the blood thereof; thou shalt pour it upon the ground as water.\"\n\n===Animal welfare===\nInformation relating to whether boiling a partially-developed embryo is ethically acceptable or not can be found in the legislation relating to the euthanasia and treatment of research animals. Bird embryos that have reached greater than 50% of their incubation have developed a [[neural tube]] sufficient for pain perception; therefore, they should be euthanized by similar methods used in avian neonates such as anesthetic overdose, decapitation, or prolonged exposure to [[carbon dioxide]].<ref name=\"AVMA\">{{cite web|title=AVMA Guidelines for the Euthanasia of Animals - 2013 edition |date=2013 |author=Leary, S. |url=https://www.avma.org/KB/Policies/Documents/euthanasia.pdf|accessdate=March 24, 2016 |publisher=AVMA|display-authors=etal}}</ref> Similarly, in the UK, embryonic birds are \"protected animals\" once they have reached the last third of their incubation period.<ref name=\"Aspa\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/consolidated-version-of-aspa-1986 |publisher=Home Office (UK) |title=Consolidated version of ASPA 1986 |year=2014 |accessdate=March 24, 2016}}</ref> There are specified methods of humanely killing protected animals used in research, but boiling is not one of these.  Depending on the species of duck, some eggs used for balut would be boiled within the last half or third of embryo development. Duck embryos are often taken off incubation in order to stunt the growth process, the embryos no longer develop, and becomes readily available for purchasing. The [[RSPCA Australia]] recommends against boiling the duck embryo from the 18th day of incubation onwards due to the potential for suffering beyond that point, and notes that it is \"an area that is yet to be further researched\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Is the practice of boiling pre-hatched duck embryos in their shell humane?|url=http://kb.rspca.org.au/Is-the-practice-of-boiling-pre-hatched-duck-embryos-in-their-shell-humane_511.html|website=RSPCA Australia knowledgebase|accessdate=October 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nSeveral groups wish to ban balut.<ref>Matejowsky, T. (2013). The Incredible, Edible Balut. Food, Culture and Society: An International Journal of Multidisciplinary Research, 16(3), 387\u2013404.</ref> A petition has been raised to get 5,000 signatures to have balut labeled \"fertilized duck egg with embryo\" and taken off the menu in the Maharlika restaurant, New York.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=http://kickerdaily.com/animal-rights-activist-stop-balut-serving-in-new-york/|title=Animal rights activist: Stop serving 'balut' in New York|website=Kicker Daily News|language=en-us|accessdate=March 20, 2016|date=April 13, 2015|author=San Jose, C.E.}}</ref> {{As of|2014}}, the restaurant was selling balut for $5 each.<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite web |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/02/05/travel/how-to-eat-balut/|publisher=CNN|year=2014|accessdate=March 24, 2016|title=Balut: The Filipino delicacy that makes the world squirm |author=Calderon, J.}}</ref> As a response to this petition, Filipino New Yorkers have created a counter petition asking to leave the food item alone.<ref name=\":7\"/>\n\n===Health===\nThe incubation temperatures and environment required for the proper development of balut during processing are ideal growth conditions for many bacteria including ''[[Salmonella enteritidis]]''. In addition, faecal [[pathogen]]s can be deposited on the egg shell surface during laying. Balut is therefore labelled as a \"Hazardous Food\" in Canada.<ref name=\":142\" /> Warnings have been published to obtain balut only from safe, well-known producers.<ref name=\":142\">{{cite web |author=Information Sheet |publisher=University of Guelph |date=2011 |title=Balut |url=http://www.myhealthunit.ca/en/partnerandhealthproviderresources/resources/EH-Food_Safety_Fact_Sheets_-_Specialty_Foods_BALUT.pdf |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404094507/http://www.myhealthunit.ca/en/partnerandhealthproviderresources/resources/EH-Food_Safety_Fact_Sheets_-_Specialty_Foods_BALUT.pdf |archive-date=April 4, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Outside Southeast Asia ==\nOutside of Southeast Asia, balut is often considered a novelty or [[taboo food]] that has been featured on reality television shows, such as in season 1 of ''[[Bizarre Foods with Andrew Zimmern]]'', or as part of eating challenges, such as on ''[[Fear Factor]]'' in 2002, ''[[Hell's Kitchen (American TV series)|Hell's Kitchen]]'' in 2013, ''[[The Amazing Race Asia 2]]'', ''[[The Amazing Race Australia 2]]'', ''[[Velyki Perehony|The Amazing Race Ukraine]]'', ''[[Survivor: Palau]]'', ''[[Survivor: China]]'', ''[[Survivor: Caramoan]]'', ''[[Survivor: Cambodia]]'', and ''[[Good Mythical Morning]]''.<ref>[http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2013/04/survivor-caramoan-its-corinne-vs-phillip-when-the-tribes-merge.html 'Survivor: Caramoan': It's Corinne vs. Phillip when the tribes merge]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/lifestyle/08/05/13/balut-gets-spotlight-new-york |title= Balut gets spotlight in New York}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, the eggs are sold at Asian markets. However, to get the right age eggs and to ensure freshness, it is recommended {{by whom|date=March 2016}} that they be purchased from a professional or an egg vendor at Asian farmers markets.\n\n[[Phillipe Nover]] of Team Nogueira ate balut during [[The Ultimate Fighter: Team Nogueira vs. Team Mir|Season 8]] of ''[[The Ultimate Fighter]]'', encouraging his teammates to do the same.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/2008/11/episode-no-8-recap-the-ultimate-fighter-team-nogueira-vs-team-mir |title= Episode No. 8 recap: \"The Ultimate Fighter: Team Nogueira vs. Team Mir\"}}</ref>{{relevance inline|date=January 2018}}\n\n==Folk medicine==\nAccording to popular Vietnamese belief, these eggs are a nutritious and restorative food for pregnant or delivering women.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n==Guinness World Record==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Townsfolk eating Balut - April 2015.jpg|thumb|upright=1.0|alt=Pateros citizens eating largest serving of balut|\t\nA huge crowd joined and witnessed the boodle fight of cooked rice with adobong ''balut''.]] -->\nOn April 10, 2015, former Pateros mayor [[Jaime \"Joey\" C. Medina]] collaborated with [[Center for Culinary Arts, Manila|Center for Culinary Arts (CCA, Manila)]] and [[History Channel|History (U.S. TV network)]] to attempt to set the record for the world's largest serving of balut. The CCA chefs, headed by Chef Tristan Encarnacion, prepared 1,000 pieces of balut into an adobo dish that was recorded to have weighed 117.5 kilograms. The resulting dish was enjoyed by the townsfolk in a symbolic [[boodle fight]], with tables topped with banana leaves stretching along B. Morcilla Street.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cnnphilippines.com/lifestyle/2015/04/12/philippines-in-world-record-attempt-for-largest-serving-of-balut.html |title=Philippines in world record attempt for largest serving of balut |publisher=CNN Philippines |date=April 14, 2015 |access-date=April 26, 2018}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/lifestyle/04/10/15/pateros-eyes-world-record-attempt-balut |title=Pateros eyes world record attempt for balut |publisher=ABS-CBN News |date=April 11, 2015 |access-date=April 27, 2018}}</ref>\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Pateros History Maker Award.jpg|thumb|right|alt=History Maker Award Joey Medina|The ''History Maker Award'' being held by Mr. Liza Morales ''(left)'' and Mayor Joey Medina ''(right)'']] -->\n\nThe record was later awarded to [[Pateros, Metro Manila]] and to this date, the record still stands.\n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/375333-largest-serving-of-balut |title=Largest serving of balut |publisher=Guinness World Records |date=April 10, 2015 |access-date=April 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Food}}\n{{div col}}\n* {{annotated link|Balut (game)}}\n* {{annotated link|Century egg}}\n* {{annotated link|Isaw}}\n* {{annotated link|Ngo_hiang|Kikiam}}\n* {{annotated link|Kutti pi}}\n* {{annotated link|Delicacy#Delicacies|List of delicacies}}\n* {{annotated link|Salted duck egg}}\n* {{annotated link|Smoked egg}}\n* {{anno